Layer 1 — Business Model Summary A two to three sentence executive characterization of what kind of business this actually is — the agency archetype that emerges from reading all four dimensions together. Not a summary of the four tabs. A single confident statement of identity that could only be written after seeing all four. This is the "here is what we understand about your business" opening statement. It names the model, the posture, and the structural logic that connects them — written as a peer-level observation, not an introduction.
Layer 2 — Cross-Dimensional Signals Three to five observations that emerge specifically from reading dimensions against each other. Each signal should name two or more dimensions in relationship — where they reinforce each other, where they create tension, or where a deliberate strategic choice in one dimension has structural implications in another. These are neither problems nor celebrations — they are pattern recognitions. Each one should have a "why this matters" statement beneath it — not what to do about it, but why this particular pattern is worth understanding. The framing is: here is what we see, and here is why it's structurally significant.
Layer 3 — Operating Realities Three to five concrete statements about what running this business at this scale and with this configuration currently requires. Not recommendations. Not changes needed. Just honest statements about what this model demands of the founder and the organization right now. These should read as the natural conclusion of the signal layer — if the signals are the observations, the operating realities are what those observations mean in practice, day to day.
Layer 4 — Synthesis Statement One to two sentences. The single most significant structural observation that emerges from reading the entire business as one integrated system. This is the closing statement of the week-two McKinsey readout — the thing that, once named, reframes how the founder sees their own business. It doesn't point forward. It completes the portrait.

On the historical versioning: The rerun architecture you described is sound and future-proofs cleanly. For V1, the foundation to lay is simply storing each dashboard synthesis run as a versioned record with a timestamp — so when a rerun fires, the previous synthesis payload is available as context. The prompt for a rerun would include the prior synthesis as an input and instruct GPT to acknowledge what has shifted versus what remains structurally consistent. The 30/60/90 day threshold for flagging meaningful time between runs is a simple date comparison that can gate whether prior context gets included or not.

Business Model Summary
The overall intent of this section
This is the landing moment. The founder just spent meaningful time going through four diagnostic tabs, sharing real numbers about their real business. When they click "Generate Your Full Report" and land here, the first thing they see needs to immediately validate that investment. Not with a generic summary — with a read that feels like someone actually absorbed what they shared and synthesized it into something they couldn't have written themselves. The emotional register is: you were paying attention, and you understood what I meant, not just what I said.

Element 1 — The Executive Headline
This is the McKinsey so-what at the page level. One declarative statement that names the single most characterizing thing about this business before the founder reads anything else. Not a title. Not a label. A sentence that, if it lands right, makes them lean in. It should feel like the opening line of a board-level readout — the thing a senior advisor would say before pulling up the first slide. This is GPT-generated, it pulls from the cross-tab synthesis, and it needs to be confident and specific enough to feel earned, not generic enough to fit any agency.
Element 2 — The Executive Summary Block
Two to four sentences — or a tight paragraph with optional supporting bullets — that give them the TLDR of the entire snapshot before they scroll into the detail layers. This isn't a summary of the four tabs sequentially. It reads the business as a system: here is what kind of business this is, here is the core structural logic connecting the dimensions, and here is the dominant pattern we see across everything you shared. This is the "we see you" moment. It should feel consultant-grade and specific — something they could forward to a COO or a board member and have it land as an accurate characterization of the business.
Element 3 — Business Vitals Strip
The five to eight key metrics pulled deterministically from the four tab records. These aren't scored or evaluated — they're stated as facts. Revenue, AGI%, margin, cash runway, churn, ACV, team size. The vitals strip does two things: it anchors the GPT synthesis in verifiable data (so it doesn't feel like opinion), and it gives the founder an immediate sense that the platform absorbed the full picture, not just one slice of it. The existing hero card pattern from the current dashboard is the right structural reference here — we're keeping that component, potentially refining the metric selection.
Element 4 — Your Agency At-a-Glance
Four dimension cards — Market Footprint, Economic Foundation, Revenue Model, and Delivery Architecture — each surfacing the synthesis headline and three core takeaways already generated from that tab's analysis. No new content is created here; this section repackages and makes accessible the work the founder has already seen. Each card is clickable, expanding into a pop-out that contains the full synthesis profile, the three beats, and the closing signal headline from that tab. Directional status indicators are removed — these cards function as navigable portraits, not evaluations. The section serves as the bridge between the system-level executive summary and the cross-dimensional signal layer: it reminds the founder what each dimension said individually before asking them to consider what those dimensions reveal in relationship to each other.

Cross-Dimensional Signals
Element 5 — Cross-Dimensional Signals
Five GPT-generated insights that emerge from reading the four dimensions against each other — each one naming a specific relationship between two or more dimensions as a tension, synergy, or structural trade-off. Each signal carries three components: a McKinsey-style descriptive headline that reads as specific to this business rather than a named framework label, a summary paragraph that articulates what the cross-dimensional relationship reveals, and a so-what statement that names the structural significance without resolving into a recommendation. The five signals are ordered narratively by the GPT call itself — not sequentially by dimension — with tension signals surfaced first, the most compounding or significant observation closing the section, and the sequencing treated as part of the synthesis rather than a formatting rule. This section is the analytical core of the dashboard: the observations that could only emerge from reading all four dimensions simultaneously, landing between the dimensional portraits of the At-a-Glance section and the lived-experience framing of the Operating Realities section that follows.

Operating Realities
Element 6 — Operating Realities
Three GPT-generated strategic implications that synthesize across the five cross-dimensional signals into higher-order conditions of the business model. Where the signals layer names specific relationships between dimensions, this section steps back and asks what those relationships collectively imply for how this business operates going forward — surfacing the structural conditions the existing model creates without framing any of them as deficits, priorities, or directives. Each implication is presented as a three-column card across the page width, carrying a concise headline that states the implication cleanly and an accordion expansion that unpacks what that condition means structurally in one short paragraph. The card layout signals equivalence rather than ranking — these are parallel conditions of the same business model, not a prioritized action list. Tone remains observational throughout: given what this business structurally is, here is what that implies. This section is the bridge between the analytical signal layer and the closing synthesis — it translates the cross-dimensional observations into the lived strategic conditions a founder would recognize as true about their business without being told what to do about them.

Synthesis Statement
Element 7 — Synthesis Statement
A GPT-generated closing statement of two to four sentences that crystallizes the integrated portrait of the business after the founder has moved through all preceding layers. Unlike the executive headline that opened the dashboard as a TLDR before the detail, the synthesis statement is earned — it lands differently because the founder has just absorbed the dimensional portraits, the cross-dimensional signals, and the structural implications, and is now ready to receive the single most resonant truth that emerges from reading everything together. The statement names the integrated condition of the business, touches on what that condition structurally makes possible or demands, and optionally orients the founder toward the horizon without directing them toward a specific next action — that work belongs to the CTA section that follows. Tone is empowering without being motivational: the clarity itself is the empowerment, not the language. It should read as the last line of a well-constructed case study — the sentence that makes everything before it feel inevitable. GPT generation for this field carries tighter constraints than any other element on the dashboard: it must feel specific enough to belong to this business and resonant enough to function as a genuine close, not a generic wrap-up statement.

CTA + Next Steps
Element 8 — Next Steps & CTA
A static, boilerplate section that serves as the intentional handoff from current state clarity to future state exploration. No GPT generation is required here — the copy, button treatment, and destination are fixed. The section carries a brief framing line that bridges the snapshot experience to the next instrument in the journey: now that the founder has a complete portrait of how their business operates today, the logical next step is visualizing what their growth scenarios look like from this starting point. The primary CTA directs them to the Growth Velocity Calculator, positioned not as a separate tool but as the natural continuation of the diagnostic journey they are already on. A secondary option allows them to return to any of the four individual tab analyses if they want to revisit a specific dimension. Visual weight is intentionally lighter than the sections that precede it — the Synthesis Statement is the emotional close, and this section is simply the door. Any personalization in this section, such as referencing the founder's revenue figure or current stage in the framing line, is a light deterministic pull rather than a GPT call, and is optional in V1.
Element 9 — Report Actions & Version Access (UI Element)
A lightweight action zone positioned near the top of the dashboard — likely adjacent to the page header — carrying two controls: a Download Report button that generates a PDF of the full dashboard output for the current snapshot run, and a View Previous Snapshots control that surfaces any prior snapshot versions the founder has completed. In V1, the View Previous Snapshots control is present but limited to viewing and downloading prior versions — no side-by-side comparison or delta analysis is exposed yet. Comparison functionality is a V2 enhancement reserved for paid tier access and will be designed separately. The data architecture must be built to support this from the start: each snapshot run is stored as a versioned record with a timestamp and an is_current flag, using INSERT-based versioning so that historical runs are preserved by default and retrievable without any schema changes at V2. The PDF download follows the same report generation pattern established elsewhere in the platform. No GPT involvement in this element — it is purely a UI and data retrieval concern.
